# ESP32-Realtime-Sensor-Monitor

> NOTE: THIS IS AN EXPANSION OF ESP32-Sensor-Dashboard

It reads temperature and humidity using a BME280 sensor and streams live data to a web page using WebSockets — no page refresh needed. The data updates instantly in the browser the moment the ESP32 has a new reading. Everything runs on millis(), no delay() used anywhere.

| ![Setup](images/setup.jpg) | ![OLED](images/oled.jpg)

---

## ✨ Features

- 🌡️ Measures temperature and humidity using a BME280 sensor
- 🖥️ Displays live data on an SSD1306 OLED screen (128x64)
- 📶 Creates its own WiFi hotspot
- 🌐 Local web server at `Your IP-address`
- ⚡ Live data streaming via WebSockets — no page refresh
- 📈 Statistics — min/max temperature and threshold count, updated live
- ⚠️ Error handling for sensor failures or loose connections
- 🔒 No sensitive data in main code
- 🧠 Non-blocking timing with `millis()` → web server stays responsive
- 🖱️ Interactive button:
  - **Short press**: shows "Button pressed!" on the OLED
  - **Long press (≥ 2 sec)**: cycles through three modes:
    - 📊 Sensor Mode — live temperature and humidity
    - ℹ️ Info Mode — device IP address and uptime
    - 📈 Stats Mode — min/max temperature and threshold count
  - **Auto-return (after 5 sec)**: returns to Sensor Mode automatically
- 🌡️ Smart alert system: reacts to high temperature with LED, OLED, and web feedback

---

## ⚡ WebSockets vs Auto-refresh

Previous projects used `setTimeout` to reload the page every 2 seconds. This project uses WebSockets — a permanent connection between the browser and the ESP32. The ESP32 pushes new data directly to the browser the moment it has a new reading. No reload, no flicker, no unnecessary requests.

---

> ⚠️ **Why no `°` symbol on the OLED?**
> The `Adafruit_SSD1306` library has limited support for special characters like the degree symbol (`°`). To keep the code simple and reliable, the OLED displays only `"C"` instead of `"°C"`.
>
> ✅ The **web version** does show the correct `°C` symbol thanks to HTML encoding.

This is a common limitation in embedded displays — not a bug!

---

## 🧰 Components Required

- ESP32 Development Board (e.g., ESP32 DevKit)
- BME280 temperature/humidity sensor (I²C)
- SSD1306 OLED display (128x64, I²C)
- Breadboard and jumper wires
- Micro-USB cable
- RED LED
- 2x 220 Ohm Resistor
- 1x pushbutton

---

## 🔌 Wiring (I²C Bus)

| ESP32 Pin | Function | Connected To |
|----------|----------|--------------|
| 3.3V | Power | VCC of BME280 + OLED |
| GND | Ground | GND of BME280 + OLED + Button (one side) |
| GPIO21 | SDA | SDA of BME280 + OLED |
| GPIO22 | SCL | SCL of BME280 + OLED |
| GPIO4 | Input | Button (other side) |
| GPIO2 | Output | LED + 220Ω resistor |

Note: The button is connected between GPIO 4 and GND. The code enables the internal pull-up resistor, so no external resistor is required.

> 💡 Ensure both devices use **different I²C addresses** (BME280: `0x76`, OLED: `0x3C`).

---

## ▶️ Usage

1. Install required libraries via PlatformIO — add these to `platformio.ini`:

```ini
lib_deps =
    adafruit/Adafruit BME280 Library@^2.2.3
    adafruit/Adafruit SSD1306@^2.5.7
    adafruit/Adafruit GFX Library@^1.11.6
    mathieucarbou/ESPAsyncWebServer@^3.3.23
    mathieucarbou/AsyncTCP@^3.3.2
```

2. Upload the code to your ESP32
3. Connect to the WiFi hotspot created by the ESP32
4. Open your browser and go to `Your IP-address`
5. Watch the data update live — no refresh needed

---

## 🧠 How It Works

The ESP32 reads temperature and humidity every 2 seconds. Instead of rebuilding and sending the entire HTML page on each update, it sends only the new values via a WebSocket connection. The browser receives the values instantly and updates only the relevant parts of the page.